{"action":"created","issue":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zarr-developers/zarr-specs/issues/267","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zarr-developers/zarr-specs","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zarr-developers/zarr-specs/issues/267/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zarr-developers/zarr-specs/issues/267/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zarr-developers/zarr-specs/issues/267/events","html_url":"https://github.com/zarr-developers/zarr-specs/issues/267","id":1934037475,"node_id":"I_kwDOCeNjb85zRxHj","number":267,"title":"Raw data type fill value endianness","user":{"login":"LDeakin","id":5069739,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjUwNjk3Mzk=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/5069739?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/LDeakin","html_url":"https://github.com/LDeakin","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LDeakin/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LDeakin/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LDeakin/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LDeakin/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LDeakin/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LDeakin/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LDeakin/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LDeakin/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LDeakin/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"labels":[],"state":"open","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":1,"created_at":"2023-10-10T00:11:15Z","updated_at":"2023-10-10T00:59:28Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"NONE","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"In the fill value metadata, there is no mention of endianness. This is fine for numerical types, as they have a native endian representation. If a chunk is missing during retrieval, it can be populated with the native endian representation of the fill value without knowledge of the codecs. However, I think raw bytes fill values are problematic because the interpretation depends on the codecs applied. A user looking at the metadata has to understand how the codecs function to know how the fill value will be interpreted.

Consider the case of decoding an array with the `gzip` and then the `endian` (soon to be `bytes`) codec. Since the most significant raw byte in the fill value is not standardised in the specification, the bytes of the fill value would need to be reordered depending on whether the endian codec is big or little endian to be consistent. The raw bytes fill value indicates what the bytes should be **after** decoding with `gzip` but **before** decoding with the `endian` codec to native endian. I think the user and implementation should not be concerned with what the fill value is in this intermediate representation. Furthermore, consider an array-to-bytes codec that does compression (e.g. [zfp](https://zfp.io/)) which does not have an endianness parameter; in this case, it is not clear which of the raw bytes is most significant.

I think the text under `Raw data types` in <https://zarr-specs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/v3/core/v3.0.html#fill-value> should explicitly state which byte is most significant. Hopefully I haven't missed something in the spec about this..
